**Approach - 1 --> Time Complexity O(n) and Space Complexity O(n)**

**Step-1** : Assign 1 candy to each children i.e in left and right array .
**Step-2** : Create a left array , that make sure to have a candy greater than left element only.
                  if(arr [ i  ] > arr [ i - 1  ]   )  then left [ i ] = left [ i - 1 ] + 1;
**Step-3** : Create a right array , that make sure to have a candy greater than right element only.
				 if( arr [ i ] > arr [ i + 1] ) then right [ i ] = right [ i +1 ] + 1;
**Step-4** : Calculate max of ( left[i] , right[i] )

E.g :
3    8    4   5   7  9
1    1    1   1   1   1    --->  left array assigned with 1
1    2    1   2   3   4   ---->  step-2
1    1    1   1   1   1   ---> right array assigned with 1
1    2    1   1   1   1   ----> step-3
calculate max of step 2 and step 3
1    2    1   2   3   4   ----------------------> ANSWER = 1 + 2+ 1+ 2+3 +4 = 13

**Note : You can also do it in a two loop with single extra array. **


**Approach - 2 : We can apply the approach of valley and peak problem.**
peek will have maximum candy while valley have 1 candy.
Initialize candy_count = no. of childern ( bcz each children must have 1 candy )
Start the looping from 1 to arr.size() -1
step -1 : if current value is equal to previous value then they have same number of Candy.
step -2 : if we have increasing slope , we increase the peak value by one for each increasing element 
``` while( arr [ i ] > arr [ i - 1 ] ) peak++;``` and add count_candy with peak value.
step - 3 : if we have decreasing slope , we increase the value of valley by one for each decreasing element
```while ( arr [ i ] < arr [ i - 1 ] ) valley++``` and add count_candy with valley value.
step -4 : count_candy = count_candy - min ( peak , valley )

