solutions.content:
The actual rating of each child doesn't really matter. 
The only thing matters is the relationship(larger/smaller) between two adjacent children, so we could convert it to a graph problem.
We can do **topological sort** to this graph and give one more candy for each level of the graph.

One thing to note that we don't need to build this graph actually. Instead simply use an array to track indegree. 
This could make the code concise and easier to implement during an interview.


```
class Solution {
    public int candy(int[] ratings) {
        int n = ratings.length;
        int[] ind = new int[n];
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++) {
            if(i!=0 && ratings[i-1] > ratings[i]) ind[i-1]++;
            if(i!=n-1 && ratings[i+1] > ratings[i]) ind[i+1]++;
        }
        Queue<Integer> q = new LinkedList<>();
        for(int i = 0; i < n; i++)
            if(ind[i] == 0) q.offer(i);

        int ans = 0;
        int level = 1;
        while(!q.isEmpty()) {
            for(int k = q.size(); k > 0; k--) {
                int idx = q.poll();
                ans+=level;
                if(idx!=0 && ratings[idx-1] > ratings[idx] && --ind[idx-1] == 0) q.offer(idx-1);
                if(idx!=n-1 && ratings[idx+1] > ratings[idx] && --ind[idx+1] == 0) q.offer(idx+1);
            }
            level++;
        }
        return ans;
    }
}
```

