# Intuition  
   If neighbour rating is less we should give that child one more candy.
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->

# Approach
At initials - give 1 candy to every child to meet the condition - every child must get a candy.

THEN 

    for loop ---------------->
      If ratings[i]>ratings[i-1]
            i+1 th child get one more candy than i th child,so increase it once
     for loop <-----------------
      If ratings[i]>ratings[i+1]
           i th child get one more candy than i+1 th child, so increase it once 


One more thing you have to keep in mind that, while reverse traversing in 2nd loop you should not give a increment to a child who already got in first loop and not required increment anymore

         example :-
     ratings              1 3 2 2 1
     candy get:-
     intitials            1 1 1 1 1
     after 1st loop       1 2 1 1 1
     after 2nd loop       1 3 1 2 1
                            ^
                            |
                        got increment twice, but dont need in 2nd loop
    so while reverse traversing we also check
               candy[i]<=candy[i+1]
                              then only it get a increment.
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->

# Complexity
- Time complexity:O(N)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity:O(N)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
class Solution {
public:
    int candy(vector<int>& ratings) {
        if(ratings.size()==1){
            return 1;
        }

        vector<int>ans(ratings.size(),1);  
        for(int i=1;i<ratings.size();i++){
            if(ratings[i]>ratings[i-1]){
                ans[i]=ans[i-1]+1;
            }
        }
        for(int i=ratings.size()-2;i>=0;i--){
            if(ratings[i]>ratings[i+1] && ans[i]<=ans[i+1]){
                ans[i]=ans[i+1]+1;
            }
        }

     return accumulate(ans.begin(),ans.end(),0LL);
    }
};
```

