# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
Basic Trapping Rainwater like solution. https://leetcode.com/problems/trapping-rain-water/

# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Observations : 
- init with all 1.
- we only give one more when we see adjacent increase (both from left to right).
- I want to use some case to illustrate this.
- notice we don't care for the exact values of ratings, only their relation

the rating is similar to 'wave', increase of decrease

let's look at this case:
```
ratings: [1,3,6,9,4,2]
candies: [1,2,3,4,2,1]
```

the highest rating is 9, when scan from left to right, num of candies should be 4, scan right to left, it should be 3, then we choose the larger value.

and let's look at some case containing adjacent-equal

when there are adjacent-equal, lets look at some cases:

```
ratings: [1,2,3,3,3,3,4,5]
candies: [1,2,3,1,1,1,2,3]
```

```
ratings: [1,2,8,8,8,8,8,2]
candies: [1,2,3,1,1,1,2,1]
```

with these cases it should be easier to understand

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
O(n)

- Space complexity:
O(n)

# Code
```
class Solution {
    public int candy(int[] ratings) {
        int[] cendies = new int[ratings.length];

        for(int i=0; i<cendies.length; ++i){
            cendies[i]=1;
        }

        for(int i=1; i<cendies.length; ++i){
            if(ratings[i]>ratings[i-1]){
                cendies[i]=cendies[i-1]+1;
            }
        }

        for(int i=cendies.length-2; i>=0; --i){
            if(ratings[i]>ratings[i+1] && cendies[i]<cendies[i+1]+1){
                cendies[i]=cendies[i+1]+1;
            }
        }

        int sum=0;
        for(int i=0; i<cendies.length; ++i){
            sum+=cendies[i];
        }
        return sum;
    }
}
```

