# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
It's a greedy problem.
Look at this example. You'll find how unfair this rule is.
```
[60, 80, 100, 100, 100, 100, 100]
```
candies for children
```
1, 2, 3, 1, 1, 1, 1
```
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Use prefix sum.It's easier to understand. Transverse forward & backward. 3 conditions to consider
1. ratings[i-1] < ratings[i]: c[i]=c[i-1]+1;
2. ratings[i-1] ==ratings[i]==ratings[i+1]: c[i]; 1 candy is enough
3. ratings[i]>ratings[i+1]: c[i]=max(c[i], c[i+1]+1); Use it when backward 

This can be done just using one loop. But the handeling is a little bit subtle.

Supposed one has arrived the peak, i.e. ```c[i]=peak+1```. From index i on, ```ratings[i]``` form a strictly decreasing sebsequence of length down+1. If peak>=down the candies for subdsequence of length ```down+1```.
```
cs=[peak+1,down, down-1, ...., 2, 1] 
```
otherwise, i.e. peak<down, when adding 1 more ```ratings[i]``` with ```ratings[i-1]>ratings[i]```
every element in ```cs```should be increased by 1 whose total amount is ```down+1```.

# Complexity
- Time complexity:
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
O(n)
- Space complexity:
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->
1st code: $O(1)$
2nd code: $O(n)$
#  Code using 1 transversal &  O(1) SC
```
class Solution {
public:
    int candy(vector<int>& ratings) {
        int n=ratings.size();
        int ans = 1;
        int up = 0, down = 0, peak = 0;
         for (int i = 1; i <n; i++) {
             //ascending
            if (ratings[i-1] < ratings[i]) {
                peak = ++up;
                down = 0;
                ans+= 1+peak;//c[i]=1+peak
            } 
            //slope=0
