# Intuition
<!-- Describe your first thoughts on how to solve this problem. -->
My very first solution contribution, based on my Python solution
# Approach
<!-- Describe your approach to solving the problem. -->
Instead of using loop twice, to solve 3 cases happened between ratings[i] and ratings[i-1]:
- ratings[i]==ratings[i-1]: new start, because no condition
- ratings[i]>ratings[i-1]: increase, and record the maximum
- ratings[i]<ratings[i-1]: add 1 at new position, but be careful for the violation:
    a. The candies from previous maximum index to the i-1th should increase by 1 to maintain the relation
    b. The candies from 1+previous maximum index should increase by 1.
I created 3 variables for curr candy (val), index of previous 'peak' (maxIdx) and number of candies at the previous peak (maxVal)
# Complexity
- Time complexity: O(n)
<!-- Add your time complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

- Space complexity: O(1)
<!-- Add your space complexity here, e.g. $$O(n)$$ -->

# Code
```
public class Solution {
    public int Candy(int[] ratings) {
        int maxVal = 1;
        int val = 1;
        int ans = 1;
        int maxIdx = 0;
        for(int i = 1; i<ratings.Length;i++){
            if(ratings[i]> ratings[i-1]){
                ++val;
                ans += val;
                maxIdx = i;
                maxVal = val;
            }
            else if(ratings[i] < ratings[i-1]) {
                val = 1;
                ans+= i - maxIdx;
                if (i - maxIdx == maxVal) {
                    maxVal+=1;
                    ans+=1;
                }
            }
            else {
                maxVal = 1;
                val =1;
                maxIdx = i;
                ans +=1;
            }
        }
        return ans;



    }
}
```

