solutions.content:
Question - 
**You are giving candies to these children subjected to the following requirements:**

- Each child must have at least one candy.
- Children with a higher rating get more candies than their neighbors.

So I thought, we can distribute candies to student with minimum ratings first, and if nearby childrens have candies, and they have lower rating than current student then we will take max of (1, 1 + candy on left, 1 + candy on right) for the current student

But you might think what if we haven't yet assigned the candy to neighbor childrens??
- It will not happen as we are going in sorted order of rating. 
- So, if we are at some rating **x+1** and neaby childrens have rating **x**, it would have been already filled. 
- And if rating of nearby children is higher, then we just assign 1 candy to this student.

```
    int candy(vector<int>& ratings) {
        vector<pair<int,int>> vec;
        int n = ratings.size();
        vec.reserve(n);

        for(int i = 0; i<n; i++){
            vec.push_back({ratings[i], i});
        }

        sort(vec.begin(), vec.end());
        vector<int> candy(n, 0);
        int ans = 0;

        for(int i = 0; i<n; i++){
            int rating = vec[i].first;
            int ind = vec[i].second;

            int candies = 1;
            if(ind > 0 && ratings[ind] > ratings[ind-1]){
                candies = max(candies, candy[ind-1] + 1);
            }
            if(ind < n-1 && ratings[ind] > ratings[ind+1]){
                candies = max(candies, candy[ind+1] + 1);
            }
            ans += candies;
            candy[ind] = candies;
        }

        return ans;
    }
```

