Draw it out on paper.

[2, 1, 1, 2, 3, 2, 3, 4, 0, 0, 1]

How many candies can be distribute? Manually plug in the values.

[2, 1, 1, 2, 3, 1, 2, 3, 1, 1, 2]

Notice that the numbers are influences by how many in a row are either ascending or descending.

Like, [1, 5, 7, 8, 100] Would requre a distribution which was [1, 2, 3, 4, 5]

And [100, 8, 7, 5, 1] Would requre a distribution which was [5, 4, 3, 2, 1]

Through inspection, we can see that the correct answer for each array slot is the max of these two values (ascending or descending).

This is how I figured it out. 





```
class Solution {
public:
    int candy(vector<int>& ratings) {

        int aCount = ratings.size();

        int aAscend[aCount + 1];
        int aStreak = 1;
        aAscend[0] = 1;
        for (int i=1;i<aCount;i++) {
            if (ratings[i - 1] < ratings[i]) {
                ++aStreak;
            } else {
                aStreak = 1;
            }
            aAscend[i] = aStreak;
        }

        int aDescend[aCount + 1];
        aDescend[aCount - 1] = 1;
        aStreak = 1;
        for (int i=aCount-2;i>=0;i--) {
            if (ratings[i + 1] < ratings[i]) {
                ++aStreak;
            } else {
                aStreak = 1;
            }
            aDescend[i] = aStreak;
        }

        int aResult = 0;

        for (int i=0;i<aCount;i++) {
            aResult += max(aAscend[i], aDescend[i]);
        }

        return aResult;
    }
};
```

